---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="About | FersMath"
  description="Why I built FersMath — a free, accurate FERS retirement calculator for federal employees."
>
  <!-- Minimal nav -->
  <header style="border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0; padding: 0 1.5rem;">
    <div
      style="max-width: 640px; margin: 0 auto; height: 3.5rem; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: space-between;"
    >
      <a
        href="/"
        style="font-weight: 700; color: #0F2244; text-decoration: none; font-size: 0.95rem;"
        >← FersMath</a
      >
      <a
        href="/calculator/high-3"
        style="font-size: 0.875rem; color: #2A7D9C; text-decoration: none; font-weight: 500;"
        >High-3 Calculator</a
      >
    </div>
  </header>

  <main style="max-width: 640px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 4rem 1.5rem 6rem;">
    <h1
      style="font-size: 1.75rem; font-weight: 800; color: #0F2244; margin: 0 0 2.5rem; line-height: 1.2;"
    >
      About this site
    </h1>

    <p
      style="font-size: 1.05rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #1e293b; margin: 0 0 1.5rem;"
    >
      I'm a federal employee. When I started trying to understand my own
      retirement, I couldn't find a single calculator that did the math
      correctly.
    </p>

    <p
      style="font-size: 1.05rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #1e293b; margin: 0 0 1.5rem;"
    >
      Most tools either ask you to enter a single salary — ignoring that your
      pay changes every year — or they round off the date arithmetic in ways
      that don't match what OPM actually does. The High-3 calculation in
      particular has real nuance: a 360-day year, 30-day months, a sliding
      window that finds your <em>highest</em> 36 months (not your last 36), and a
      pay table that rolls over every January 1st. Get any of that wrong and the number
      is off.
    </p>

    <p
      style="font-size: 1.05rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #1e293b; margin: 0 0 1.5rem;"
    >
      So I built the calculator I wanted to exist. It uses published OPM pay
      tables, splits your career history at year boundaries automatically, and
      shows you exactly which months contributed to your High-3 and by how much.
    </p>

    <p
      style="font-size: 1.05rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #1e293b; margin: 0 0 3rem;"
    >
      Everything here is free. No account, no email, no ads. If it's useful,
      <a
        href="https://buymeacoffee.com/matanov"
        style="color: #2A7D9C; text-decoration: underline;"
        >buying me a coffee</a
      >
      helps keep it running.
    </p>

    <hr
      style="border: none; border-top: 1px solid #e2e8f0; margin: 0 0 3rem;"
    />

    <h2
      style="font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #0F2244; margin: 0 0 1.25rem;"
    >
      This is also a learning project
    </h2>

    <p
      style="font-size: 1.05rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #1e293b; margin: 0 0 1.5rem;"
    >
      I'm using this site as a hands-on way to get better at modern software
      practices. Every calculator ships through a CI/CD pipeline — push to
      GitHub, automated build, deployed to production in under a minute. No
      manual steps, no FTP, no crossing fingers.
    </p>

    <p
      style="font-size: 1.05rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #1e293b; margin: 0 0 1.5rem;"
    >
      The code is written with the help of AI — Claude for architecture and
      logic, a local model for autocomplete. I find it genuinely changes how
      fast you can move on a solo project, but it still requires knowing what
      you're building and why. The AI doesn't know OPM's 360-day rule. You have
      to.
    </p>

    <p
      style="font-size: 1.05rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #1e293b; margin: 0 0 3rem;"
    >
      The stack is Astro, React, TypeScript, Tailwind v4, and GitHub Actions.
      Nothing exotic — just tools that work well together and are worth knowing.
    </p>

    <hr
      style="border: none; border-top: 1px solid #e2e8f0; margin: 0 0 3rem;"
    />

    <h2
      style="font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #0F2244; margin: 0 0 1.25rem;"
    >
      What's here now
    </h2>
    <ul
      style="margin: 0 0 3rem; padding: 0 0 0 1.25rem; color: #334155; line-height: 2;"
    >
      <li>
        <a
          href="/calculator/high-3"
          style="color: #2A7D9C; text-decoration: none;"
          >High-3 Average Salary Calculator</a
        > — OPM-compliant, uses real GS pay tables
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2
      style="font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #0F2244; margin: 0 0 1.25rem;"
    >
      What's coming
    </h2>
    <ul
      style="margin: 0 0 3rem; padding: 0 0 0 1.25rem; color: #334155; line-height: 2;"
    >
      <li>FERS Basic Annuity Calculator</li>
      <li>TSP Projection Calculator</li>
      <li>FERS Supplement Estimator</li>
      <li>Retirement Eligibility Checker (MRA, MRA+10, MRA+30)</li>
    </ul>

    <hr
      style="border: none; border-top: 1px solid #e2e8f0; margin: 0 0 3rem;"
    />

    <h2
      style="font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #0F2244; margin: 0 0 1.25rem;"
    >
      A note on accuracy
    </h2>
    <p
      style="font-size: 1.05rem; line-height: 1.8; color: #1e293b; margin: 0 0 1.5rem;"
    >
      I've tested the High-3 math extensively against OPM's published rules.
      That said, I'm not a financial advisor or an HR specialist. Use this to
      understand your situation — then verify the final numbers with your agency
      HR office before making any retirement decisions.
    </p>
  </main>
</Layout>
